  <thing id="t5CVampire" name="Vampire" description="VAMPIRES ARE AMONG THE most enduringly popular monsters of folklore and mythology. From the ageold tales of the peasantry to the smash hits of Bram Stoker, Anne Rice, and Stephanie Meyers, vampires have captured the imagination as creatures of both revulsion and desire. Numerous video games, books, movies, and TV shows feature vampire protagonists, and so many people want to role-play as vampires that there are entire RPG lines devoted to the subject.\n\nThis document presents rules for playing vampire characters in 5th Edition. BEWARE! Vampire characters are more complicated than ordinary PHB classes and races. Vampires are extremely powerful, but come with a host of equally troublesome weaknesses and vulnerabilities. Usually when a person wishes to play a vampire it’s because they want this level of complexity—they want to struggle against supernatural flaws and exhibit weird powers. But the DM needs to make sure that these drawbacks don’t interfere with the fun had by the other players.\n\nVAMPIRE TEMPLATE\nA player character slain by a vampire’s bite attack may rise the next night as a vampire spawn. They gain all of the features listed in the vampire template on page 4, plus the Enthralled feature: Enthralled. As a vampire spawn, you are charmed by the vampire that killed you (your master). While charmed, you must obey your master’s spoken commands. You remain charmed until your master is destroyed or until you drink your master’s blood.\n\nIf your master orders you to act against your alignment, bonds, or ideals, you may make a Wisdom saving throw (DC 8 + your master’s proficiency bonus + your master’s Charisma modifier). On a success, you are no longer charmed.\n\nFORMER VAMPIRES\nA vampire character who is killed and then raised from the dead becomes a living creature again. You lose the vampire template and all of its features. \n\nIf you have levels in the vampire class and are restored to life, you lose all vampire class features except your hit points, hit dice, proficiencies, and proficiency bonus. You retain your level for effects that depend on level. You also retain the Ability Score Improvement and Extra Attack features, if you have them. If you die, you may rise as a vampire at the next sundown, regaining your vampire class features. \n\nEach time you gain a level while alive, you may retroactively convert one of your vampire levels into a level of another class. Replace all the features of the vampire class at your highest class level with the features of the new class at its next\nlevel." compset="Template" uniqueness="unique">
